metadata.name: Illusion City #300
metadata.description:
Illusion City reflects the variety of Istanbul by its different and divergent zones, day and night, humid summers and ice cold winters, colorful neighborhoods and giant plazas, its never ending human and vehicle traffic.

This series is an expression of how we experience this city, kind of like a love and hate relationship. The city that is a cradle of civilizations now has become a concrete jungle. Our beautiful city and its citizens are now trying to find their own balance in this state of chaos.

We wanted to express these complex emotions with a long-form generative artwork since it is the most suitable medium to explore every possible combination of emotions we have about our city. 

Best experienced in full screen.

Probabilities;

- 3 pre-made color palettes, 1 generative color palette

- 3 blend modes

- 3 topping placements

- 8 different particle angle compositions

- Several grid sizes and edges

- An intentionally kept in glitch (rare)

In live mode, press ‘s’ to save as .png (2000 x 2666 px )

It can take up to a minute to render or longer in low-performance computers. Enjoy the process!

Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, July 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Chordal Reveries #40
metadata.description:
[ CLICK TO START THE SOUND ]

In the realm of creativity and introspection, often the most remarkable moments arise when we are being curious and present. Embracing a playful mindset, free from the constraints of predefined goals or the need to prove oneself, is something that guides towards that. "Chordal Reveries" is a self-playing musical instrument that perpetually produces captivating melodies. At the same time, it invites you to explore and collaborate while practicing the art of living in the present moment.

Within this experience, eight marbles navigate a captivating glass labyrinth, triggering sounds along their path. Each marble can be individually activated or deactivated using the controls. Additionally, eight knobs offer control over the camera and some aspects of the generated sounds. The interactions and their corresponding GUI have been designed with the AKAI LPD8 MIDI controller in mind. However, the same controls can also be accessed through keyboard combinations. 

Controls
[ 1 - 8 ] - toggle marbles
[ shift & 1 - 8 ] - increase the value of a knob
[ shift & ctrl & 1 - 8 ] - decrease the value of a knob
[ r ] - reset parameters to defaults
[ finger ] - control the camera
[ s ] - save the current frame as an image
[ f ] - fullscreen

Created with Three.js & Tone.js
Copyright (c) March - June 2023 Shaderism

metadata.name: Calligraphy #188
metadata.description:
Calligraphy is about formulating letters, not language. 

One of my first exercises as a design student (c. 1967) was learning to letter. Using a nib holding pen and India ink we sat for 5 weeks in class like monks constructing letters in the style of a font called 15th Century Chancery Italic Script. Our final grade was based on how well we hand lettered a paragraph. It was a grueling process that's why I remember it; quite the way to develop an appreciation for the letterforms and type faces. 

This algorithmic artwork is modern cuneiform. It is based on a theory I've developed called "Language of Vision" which in itself is an approach for creating a "plastic" image. The space-frame or background square consists of a subtle paper texture and defines the tablet. A resizable tile (spatial force) forms the boundary for a "stroke." The stroke within the tile element is created by joining two bezier curves. 

An algorithm called "fractions of the whole" is a "form of spatial organization" which divides the picture frame into randomly sized intervals along each axes that form the variable sized tile areas. The stroke is programmed to fit each area. This theory lends itself very nicely to algorithmic art and provides a general framework for generative art.

There is meaning in every image but that meaning comes from your experience and imagination.

Check out Dr. Bill Generative Art OG website @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: .cloths (Japan color) #54
metadata.description:
For this Token, I was inspired by Japanese culture and incorporated colors traditionally associated with Japan into the palette.

The traditional Japanese colors, regularly tiled, resemble the scales of Nishikigoi or the patterns of a kimono (furisode) patterns.

The shearing deformation of the tile shapes; shear() makes the colors appear abstract.

The palette is selected from one of the following variations.

01. Ninja(忍者)　02. Tsukimi(月見)　03. Fuji & Moon(富士と月)　04. Urushi(漆)　05. Red Fuji(赤富士)　06. Tonosama(殿様)　07. Daimyo(大名)　08. Cherry Blossom(桜)　09. Autumn Leaves(紅葉)　10. Furisode(振り袖)　11. Nishikigoi(錦鯉)　12. Uji Kintoki(宇治金時)　13. Samurai(侍)

I would be happy if you could feel the beauty of Japan, my birthplace, even a little.



Generative art by @ConatusLab

Built in Javascript with p5.js.

Press 's(S)' to save a png.

metadata.name: MetaSignal: Lexicon #47
metadata.description:
The project is a reinterpretation of my previous "MetaSignal", with a different key.

Two one-dimensional 3-states cellular automata intersect to form a grid with a total of nine states.
A two-dimensional cellular automata extracts details from the grid.

This complex configuration enhances the veil of mystery surrounding how intricate and captivating structures emerge from simple random rulesets.
I invite you to search and reflect about the hidden layers of meaning, hoping you will find yours.

---

16 messages, 3 sampling methods, a small probability of receiving a broken signal.

• Clicking/tapping on the canvas shows a menu to pause, resume, reverse generation direction and download the current 1080x1080 pixels frame.

Done with p5.js
Simone "OuterSilent" Ferrari | IG: @outertales | September 2023

   Per aspera ad astra.

metadata.name: Rapport #109
metadata.description:
The concept of nexus is a powerful one. It speaks to the idea that everything is related and that each part is necessary to create the whole. Rapport is about the relationship these parts have, harmonious or discordant, to convey a sense of unity and purpose. You are invited to explore the details and interactions of each object in its surroundings, recognizing the immense value they all have in building greater things.

A few shortcuts are available in live mode:
1 : Toggle the view (fit screen / original size)
T : Toggle paper texture
S : Save current view
H : Re-render in high resolution

The piece might require high processing power depending on its features. A good desktop or laptop running chrome is recommended.

Created with p5.js and GLSL
dmarchi, 2023.

metadata.name: glory hole$ #577
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: Breakdown #85
metadata.description:
The key to solving a difficult problem is to break it down into a series of smaller, more tractable, problems.

Here we start with a rectangular polygon. We shrink our polygon by some fixed amount (inset), and then pick a point inside it. We then send off rays in N evenly spaced directions and use these to split the polygon into N new polygons. Repeat the process, varying parameters such as how we pick our point or the angles of our projected rays, and see what emerges.

Press 'v' to download an svg output.
